# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Troubleshooting
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# Error: "Can't reach database server at aws-0-..."
# Solution: 
# - Check password is correct (no special characters need encoding)
# - Verify project is not paused (7 days inactivity pauses project)
# - Check internet connection

# Error: "Prepared statement already exists"
# Solution:
# - Use pooled connection (pgbouncer=true) for runtime
# - Use direct connection for migrations only

# Error: "Too many connections"
# Solution:
# - Add connection_limit=1 to pooled connection
# - Use connection pooling (port 6543)
# - Check for connection leaks in code

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Security Best Practices
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# 1. NEVER commit connection strings to Git
# 2. Use different passwords for dev/staging/production
# 3. Rotate database password periodically
# 4. Use environment variables for all sensitive data
# 5. Enable Row Level Security (RLS) in Supabase for production
# 6. Monitor database activity in Supabase dashboard
# 7. Set up daily backups (Supabase provides automatic backups)

